After the liberal international order
CAMBRIDGE – Many analysts believe that the liberal international order ended with China’s rise and US President Donald Trump’s election.
But if Joe Biden defeats Trump in the November election, should he strive to revive it?
Perhaps not, but he must find some alternative.
Critics are correct to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very free.
It excludes more than half the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian states.
US hegemony is always overstated.
Nevertheless, the most powerful countries must take the lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they will not be provided – and Americans will suffer for it.
The current pandemic is a good example of this.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to build rule-based international institutions that bring different members together to deal with different issues.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, neither country was able to balance American power, which was obsessed with pursuing freedom values at the expense of sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without UN Security Council approval.
It also supported a “Responsibility to Protect” resolution adopted by the UN General Assembly in 2005, aimed at protecting citizens who suffer brutal treatment by their own governments – which the US then invoked in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as the arrogance of post-Cold War Americans – for example, when Russia and China felt cheated when NATO’s intervention in Libya eventually led to regime change – while defenders see it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Nevertheless, the growth of Chinese and Russian power more strictly limits the scope for liberal interventionism.
So what remains?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereign principles enshrined in the UN Charter, which stipulate that states can only go to war in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the forcible occupation of another country's territory has been rare, and when it does occur, it comes at a high cost in sanctions (as seen in Russia's annexation of Crimea in 2014).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, while political cooperation has successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This rules-based order dimension remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will be a decoupling of global supply chains, especially when national security is threatened.
While China complaints about the US blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G networks in the West, the US stance aligns with sovereignty demands.
After all, China has prevented Google, Facebook, and Twitter from operating within its borders for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules could help prevent the decoupling from escalating.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
Conversely, interdependence in the ecological domain faces insurmountable barriers in the face of sovereignty, as threats transcend national boundaries.
While economic globalization may suffer setbacks, environmental globalization will continue because it follows biological and physical laws that contemporary geopolitical logic cannot overcome.
These issues threaten everyone, but no single country has the capacity to solve them on its own.
In issues like the COVID-19 pandemic in 2019 and climate change, power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions.
Under such circumstances, thinking only about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also think about exercising power together with other countries.
The Paris Climate Agreement and the World Health Organization benefit us and everyone else.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, this did not impede Sino-US cooperation.
The challenge Biden faces is whether the US and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while competing in traditional great-power rivalry areas.
The internet is a new and important issue – because it has a partly transnational nature but is also subject to sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially fragmented.
Rules on internet freedom of speech and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace recommends, if authoritarians also want to achieve interconnectedness, certain rules that prohibit tampering with the basic structure of the internet would also serve their interests.
But when they use proxies to wage information wars or interfere in elections (which infringe on sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules like those negotiated during the Cold War to limit the escalation of maritime incidents (despite ongoing ideological hostility).
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare the norms they intend to uphold and build the necessary deterrence.
Maintaining free values in cyberspace does not mean unilateral disarmament for the US.
Instead, the US should distinguish between permissible forms of soft power such as open persuasion and hard power such as covert information warfare, and be prepared to strike back when the latter is employed against it.
Russia and China can be allowed to broadcast programs openly, but manipulating social media and other covert unified actions are not permitted.
Moreover, the US will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Polls show that American public opinion wants to avoid military intervention but does not want to exit alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still values certain principles.
If Biden is elected, the question he faces will not be whether to restore the liberal international order.
The question is whether the United States can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights, and at the same time cooperate with a broader set of countries to manage rule-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyberattacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
